<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Congratulates Japan's Mori  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton called Japan's new
prime minister Wednesday night with congratulations and assurances
that the United States would work closely with him.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiro Mori, a former trade minister, was sworn in earlier in
the day to succeed Keizo Obuchi, who suffered a stroke Sunday and
went into a coma.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton placed the call soon after flying from Washington to his
Westchester County home for a night's stay. The president expressed
sorrow over Obuchi's stroke but congratulated Mori on his election,
White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He assured Prime Minister Mori of our desire to work closely
with him on the wide-ranging issues we have in common,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
