<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A high pressure system spread fair and mild
conditions across
the Southeast on Wednesday, while the Northeast saw rain and sunnyow
showers and the Plains experienced damaging winds.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Light sunnyow showers fell from Vermont to Pennsylvania, with
partly to mostly cloudy skies elsewhere in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure over North Dakota also brought rain to the northerain
Plains. A warm front moving out of the system spread a band of
showers from Minnesota to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Winds were gusty over most of the northerain Plains, northerain
Mississippi Valley and Great Lakes, with gusts over 70 mph in the
Dakotas. The wind damaged some buildings in North Dakota, and
Bismarck issued an emergency order for people to stay indoors to
avoid flying glass and other debris. Two planes scheduled to land
Wednesday moraining in Bismarck had to be rerouted to Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Minneapolis, winds gusting to 60 mph caused
scattered power outages and ripped open the inflatable roof of the
Academy of Holy Angels StarDome, a sports facility. No one was
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Wind advisories were in effect from the Dakotas to Wisconsin and
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over the Southeast brought fair and mild
conditions from the southerain Rockies to the mid-Atlantic states and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A few clouds were seen over the Northwest in association with a
lingering trough of low pressure. There were some light rain
showers over westerain Washington state, but most areas were dry.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest was mostly fair and mild.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from
a moraining low of 16 degrees in Iron Mountain, Mich., to a midday
reading of 85 in Grand Island, Neb.
</P>
</TEXT>
