<HEADLINE> Auctioneers Doing Well in Thailand  </HEADLINE>
By NINA SUEBSUKCHAROEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Auctions have become a way of life in
Thailand, perhaps proving that recession as much as necessity can
be the mother of invention.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and condominiums, rare paintings and racy cars are
among the items going before the hammer as Thais try to climb out
of economic crisis. Experts say the auctions have helped smooth out
recovery and provided those who have cash with some real bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Auctions are a new choice for consumers,'' said Kritika
Kongsompong, one of the owners of the Union Auction Co. ''The
buyers dictate the market price.''
</P>
<P>
   In the larger scheme, James Pitchon, executive director of the
real estate firm CB Richard Ellis (Thailand) Co., said property
auctions, some of it collateral for bad loans made by banks, is
reducing the banks' heavy debt loads -- a main drag on Thailand's
economic rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden interest in auctions began when the Financial Sector
Restructuring Authority, a specially formed government agency,
started liquidating the assets of 56 finance firms shut down for
insolvency after the onset of the Asian currency crisis in
mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last year, the authority had sold $4.91 billion
worth of seized assets originally valued at $17.63 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Last month it auctioned 66 rare paintings and 2,151 rare bank
notes with the help of the Thai subsidiary of Christie's, the New
York auction house. About $231,000 was earned from the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the authority is seeking to auction off the
non-listed securities of the suspended finance firms.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of auctions, at the nadir of Thailand's
financial crisis in 1998, disposed of more mundane items such as
cars and office furniture from the defunct finance firms.
</P>
<P>
   The authority went to the private sector to handle those sales,
hiring Union Auction to conduct the auctions, which ended up
pumping up the company's business and jump-starting the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Laksak Arunwatana, a bank employee, came away from such auctions
with a near-new Toyota sedan at 10 percent to 15 percent under the
retail price and a townhouse at 20 percent below market value.
</P>
<P>
   ''Auctions are beneficial to buyers in these bad economic
times,'' Laksak said.
</P>
<P>
   Union Auction has also benefitted. The company had 1999 revenue
of $115.8 million, a 42 percent increase over the previous year.
Revenue from automobile auctions grew by 31 percent, to $100
million, while property auctions exploded 356 percent to $14.6
million from $3.2 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenal growth has prompted two other auction houses to
target real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Realty Co. teamed up with American auctioneers Mel
Giller and Associates. Apichart Archadej, the company's managing
director, said he will focus on financial institutions, which have
a very big inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Asset Auction Center, which held its first property auction
early this year, will be holding auctions every other month
throughout the year, said Khaimook Churawat, the company's head of
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping malls are also jumping into the game, holding auctions
to promote business. IT Mall, a relatively new computer superstore,
has held several auctions of computer paraphernalia and electrical
goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-06-00 0023 </TRAILER>
