<HEADLINE> Pollster says religious vote is misunderstood  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The ''Catholic vote'' doesn't exist and
jewish voters are misunderstood, pollster John Zogby told a group
of reporters on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby, who spoke at the New York State Associated Press
Association's spring seminar about voter moods, said that the
values of voters are too conflicting to be categorized according to
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ''The same voter who answers a poll saying that they are for a
woman's right to choose, will say that killing a fetus is murder,''
Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no Catholic vote in the U.S. or in New York...and the
Jewish vote is misunderstood to be a one issue, pro-Israel at all
costs group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby found that two-fifths of Jewish voters live in the suburbs
and vote for moderate Republicans. Using the U.S. Senate race
between Hillary Rodham Clinton and presumptive opponent New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as an example, Zogby described them as
part of ''that white ethnic commuter group who likes what Rudy's
done with the city,'' as opposed to ''knee jerk liberal'' urban
voters.
</P>
<P>
   And while recent polls show Clinton winning New York City,
Giuliani still enjoys a margin over the first lady in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics, who make up 45 percent of New York state's
electorate, are similarly diverse, Zogby said. Catholic voters who
attend mass regularly tend to be conservative, while those who
don't go to mass are quite liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ''And there are more of them on the left than right,'' Zogby
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of a consistent Jewish or Catholic voting
ideology, both Clinton and Giuliani have made concerted efforts to
court voters of each group.
</P>
<P>
   Both have met with rabbis and Orthodox leaders in hopes of
winning over New York's 12 percent Jewish vote. In February, the
mayor of Jerusalem went to New York City to express support for
Giuliani, and in November, the prime minister of Israel defended
Clinton's actions in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been criticized for sitting silently beside Soha
Arafat, wife of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, while she accused
Israelis of using poisonous gas against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Giuliani is expected to win the votes of most Catholics
in the state, but Clinton has won the backing of some vocal
Irish-American groups, which indicates some Catholic support.
</P>
<P>
   A Quinnipiac College Poll released Wednesday showed that among
Jewish voters, Giuliani has lost the 10 point lead he enjoyed over
Clinton on March 2. The first lady now leads by 4 points.
</P>
<P>
   And a Marist College poll from March 29 shows Giuliani leading
Clinton 55-32 among the state's white Catholic voters.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Zogby, none of that is set in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things change,'' he said, explaining that polls have shown the
same religious group supporting liberal former Gov. Mario Cuomo one
year and conservative former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato the next.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like you walk into a bar and find five guys who haven't
gone to mass in 40 years. But insult the pope, and they're there
with fists up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-06-00 0046 </TRAILER>
