<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's claims of 'extra burdens' for political women rebutted  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Comments Hillary Rodham Clinton made
recently about the 'extra burdens' women face in running for office
reek of the ''tired rhetoric of the 70s'' according to a female
Republican in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's an opportunity and a privilege, not a burden, to
run for office,'' said Erie County Sen. Mary Lou Rath on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rath and 10 others, one short of all the female Republicans in
the Legislature, said they are happy with women's place in New York
politics, even though no female has ever been elected governor,
comptroller or attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Three women have been elected lieutenant governor in New York,
all running jointly on tickets headed by male gubernatorial
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the system works,'' Rath said, adding that the U.S.
Senate candidate's comments seem like ''the tired rhetoric of the
70s and I think most of us have rejected that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has commented on the sexism of politics several
times during her campaign against New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, most recently at a campaign stop just south of Albany
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There, the Democrat said ''there are extra burdens that women
(candidates) face around the country.'' She added female candidates
need ''skin as tough as a rhinoceros.''
</P>
<P>
   She also told an Albany radio station in late January that
people could dislike her because of her political stances or
because she is a woman taking those stances.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson declined to comment
Wednesday, but U.S. Rep Nita Lowey, a Democrat from Westchester
County, backed the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've made a lot of progress on women's rights in this
country, but women still face tremendous hurdles in politics,
business and virtually every other professional field,'' she said.
''Everyone knows that. Why else would we have only 67 women in the
House and Senate?''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP lawmakers, while often referring to their children and
home lives, said they support Giuliani's stance on the fatal
shooting of Patrick Dorismond by New York City police last month.
In defending the shooting of the unarmed black man, Giuliani made
public Dorismond's criminal record -- including court-sealed
juvenile records -- and did not visit the man's family.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show Giuliani may have suffered because of that
stance, but when asked what she would do if it had been her child
shot, Assemblywoman Donna Ferrara, from Nassau County, said, ''I
would not have expected a public official to speak to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rath acknowledged women face different challenges than men when
running for office, especially how to balance family and work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some challenges of running seem daunting, but they're not
burdens,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The group also suggested Clinton might be unfamiliar with the
way New York politics work -- since she hadn't lived or worked in
New York until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Her comments show ''she's unfamiliar with elected women across
the state,'' Ferrara said. ''We have greater opportunities because
we're women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-06-00 0047 </TRAILER>
