<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 11, Phillies 3  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Lenny Harris hit a grand slam during a six-run
first inning and Mike Morgan got his first save in nine years as
the Arizona Diamondbacks beat the Philadelphia Phillies 11-3
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Lee had a solo shot for the Diamondbacks, who got all
their runs on homers in Tuesday night's season-opening 6-4 win over
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Stottlemyre (1-0), who worked out daily during the
offseason to strengthen an unrepaired tear in his right rotator
cuff, gave up three runs and six hits -- including Scott Rolen's
second solo homer in two games -- in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan became the 25th major leaguer to play in four decades
when he relieved starting the sixth. He allowed three hits in four
scoreless innings for his fourth career save, his first since July
7, 1991, with Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is Morgan's 12th team, a record for a franchise in any
U.S. major league.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia starter Paul Byrd (0-1) got just two outs, giving
up six runs, three hits and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Womack tripled on Byrd's third pitch and scored on Jay
Bell's sacrifice fly. Byrd walked Luis Gonzalez and Erubiel Durazo,
and Steve Finley had RBI single. Travis Lee walked to load the
bases and Harris followed with his third career slam.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Byrd walked Stottlemyre and was taken out of the
game. Former-Diamondback Amaury Telemaco relieved and ending the
inning by striking out Womack.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia made it 6-3 in the second on Rolen's homer, Mickey
Morandini's RBI single and Desi Relaford's run-scoring, double-play
grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Stinnett hit a two-run double off Telemaco in the third,
and Lee homered off Wayne Gomes in the seventh. Lee added a
sacrifice fly in the eighth and Finley had an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Harris' slam was Arizona's 14th in two-plus seasons.
history. ... Finley, who was 4-for-4 in the opener, had a
broken-bat single in the first for his fifth consecutive hit before
his first out of the season -- a fly ball to center in the second.
... ... Morandini, who spent the last two years with the Chicago
Cubs, saw action for the first time on his second tour with the
Phillies. Morandini played in 874 games with the Phillies before
they traded him to Chicago for Doug Glanville on Dec. 23, 1997. ...
Morgan singled in his only at-bat, his 48th hit in 480 career
at-bats (.100). His previous hit was July 10, 1999, with Texas at
San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
