<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oneidas disappointed at breakdown of land claim talks  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERONA, N.Y. (AP) -- Barring a return to the bargaining table,
the Oneida Indian land claim likely is headed to federal court.
That makes Ray Halbritter a disappointed man.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nation's Men's Council and Clan Mothers do not want to be
forced to court to settle this,'' Halbritter, the representative of
the Oneida Indian Nation, said Wednesday at the tribe's Turning
Stone Casino. ''We have worked hard for more than a year to avoid
litigation and to reach a settlement that would fairly address
everyone's concerns. We have always believed that the best way to
resolve the land claim is through negotiation. We are deeply
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations, on fragile ground just a month ago, had been
progressing again until late Tuesday afternoon. Settlement master
Ron Riccio abruptly called an impasse because he said not every
party was committed to the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's over. I don't see any hopes of getting it revived,''
Riccio said before drafting a letter to explain what had happened
in detail to U.S. District Court Judge Neal McCurn. ''I invested
more time in this than in any other mediation I've ever had, and
I've done many of these over the years. In a mediation, where you
can't order anything to happen and you have to rely upon the
cooperation of the parties, it is very easy for someone to cause
the process to fail no matter what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The land claim stems from the state's purchase of 250,000 acres
in Madison and Oneida counties from the Oneidas of New York,
Wisconsin and Canada in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas filed a lawsuit in 1974 over the transactions. The
U.S. Supreme Court found in 1985 that those transactions were
illegal and ruled that the Oneidas were entitled to compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the federal government sided with the Oneidas and filed
an amended complaint asking that 20,000 landowners in the two
counties be added as defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Halbritter detailed the tribe's position in the negotiations. He
said the Oneida Nation offered to pay the counties a fee of $1
million per year for 20 years, agreed to charge its own sales tax
to ensure tax and price parity with other local businesses on such
items as cigarettes and gasoline, and agreed to use state and
federal settlement funds to establish a $25 million land trust fund
to replace property taxes lost through the reacquisition of its
ancestral homelands.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major stumbling blocks was land. The tribe said it
would agree to acquire no more than 5,000 acres in the first 10
years after the settlement, no more than 30,000 acres in a 50-year
period, and no more than 40,000 acres overall.
</P>
<P>
   But Madison County Board of Supervisors Chairman Rocco
DiVeronica said the counties balked at allowing the purchase of
more than 25,000 acres. He said that was the limit constituents had
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   State officials also expressed dismay over the cessation of
talks. Gov. George Pataki was drafting a letter to President
Clinton in an effort to get the federal government out of the case,
Pataki spokesman Mike McKeon said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've very disappointed that the Oneidas walked away over the
land-cap issue despite the counties' willingness to be flexible,''
McKeon said. ''Hopefully, we can get back to the table. We're ready
to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Halbritter said the amount of land the Oneidas are seeking to
reacquire was insignificant considering what the tribe once had.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Oneidas originally owned 6 million acres, and now it's
down to 250,000 acres,'' he said. ''And we're willing to accept 15
percent of what our total claim is.''
</P>
<P>
   Halbritter said the state also created a major stumbling block
by continuing to demand a substantial share of Turning Stone's
profits as a condition for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We simply cannot and will not agree to pay for the state's
wrongdoing,'' he said. ''We've done that for the past 200 years.
We're not going to pay for our own land claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Although negotiations still could resume, the case seems
destined to end up in front of McCurn, who is all-too-familiar with
the process. A jury settled a similar dispute in his Syracuse
courtroom in February involving the Cayuga Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Cayugas successfully argued that 64,015 acres of their
tribal lands were illegally purchased in the late 1790s and early
1800s by New York state and were awarded $36.9 million. However,
they are planning an appeal, which will drag the process on.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a scenario the Oneidas want to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The really bad news with the collapse of these talks is that
we're headed back to court,'' Halbritter said. ''Going back to
court is in no one's interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-06-00 0047 </TRAILER>
