<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third poll shows mayor's support down; campaigns spar on debates  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- If bad news comes in threes, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani now has the polls to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute reported
that the New York City mayor's lead over Hillary Rodham Clinton in
New York's Senate race has evaporated in the wake of the shooting
of an unarmed black man by New York City police. It was the third
such poll in 10 days to show that.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac poll had the first lady favored by 46 percent of
registered voters while 43 percent backed the mayor. Giuliani led
Clinton, 48 percent to 41 percent, in a March 2 poll from the
Hamden, Conn.-based institute.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier polls, from Zogby International for the New York Post
and from Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion, showed
similar results.
</P>
<P>
   The polls come at a time when some Republicans are questioning
whether the mayor is the best candidate to take on the first lady.
On Sunday, U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio said the GOP was in danger of
''blowing'' the Senate race by backing Giuliani. The Long Island
congressman offered himself as an alternative, if GOP leaders
wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gov. George Pataki said Lazio should shelve any
such thoughts and get behind Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's particularly helpful for other Republicans
to do anything other than get behind the candidacy of Mayor
Giuliani,'' the Republican governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Giuliani's campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum,
sent his counterpart in the Clinton campaign, Bill de Blasio, a
letter asking for a meeting to discuss possible debates. Teitelbaum
said the mayor had expressed interest in debates ''several week
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter back, de Blasio said that ''in Buffalo on February
22, Hillary challenged Mr. Giuliani to a series of debates in every
part of the state. I'm sorry it has taken you so long to respond,
but I guess Mr. Giuliani's falling poll numbers necessitated a
change in your strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said de Blasio planned to call Teitelbaum to set up a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum called de Blasio's written response a ''stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, Mrs. Clinton would rather bob and weave than engage
in a direct discussion of the issues,'' the Giuliani aide said.
</P>
<P>
   With the mayor in Tennessee raising money for his campaign,
Clinton staged a full day of campaigning in New York City and on
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he's been having a bad couple of weeks,'' the first
lady said when asked about her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the poll, Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Juleanna
Glover Weiss said that ''in light of the recent media coverage,
this is not unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute, said the new poll showed ''a dramatic drop'' for the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the first time in months that Mrs. Clinton has been on
the plus side in this very close race and there's a one-word
explanation -- Dorismond,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Dorismond was fatally shot by New York City police last
month. In defending the police in the shooting of the unarmed black
man, Giuliani made public Dorismond's criminal record, including
court-sealed juvenile records. That has drawn heavy criticism of
the mayor, including some from fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Attention on the issue in New York City doesn't figure to
diminish soon. About 700 protesters rallied near City Hall on
Wednesday, and one group was removed by police after briefly
blocking traffic on the Brooklyn Bridge. Many protesters chanted
''Giuliani must go!''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rev. Al Sharpton, who led regular protests last year
after the Amadou Diallo shooting, announced plans Wednesday for
daily acts of civil disobedience around the city during Easter week
to draw attention to police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 50 percent of voters said they disapproved of
Giuliani's response to the Dorismond shooting, with the greatest
disapproval coming from New York City (72 percent) and in the
suburban counties surrounding the city (54 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac's telephone poll of 1,058 registered voters was
conducted March 28-April 3 and has a margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net: polling institute site: www.quinnipiac.edu.
</P>
</TEXT>
