<DOCNO> APW20000406.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fraud probe could spread to Bennett's wife  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Gwen Bennett has had a close look as
federal authorities have prosecuted her husband for cheating
investors out of $700 million. She may soon have an insider's view.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mrs. Bennett's legal advisers fears remarks made by a
federal judge indicate that she, too, may be prosecuted in
connection with what authorities have called the largest pyramid
scheme ever uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bennett appeared in a Manhattan federal courtroom last
week ready to be sentenced for fraud. Instead, U.S. District Judge
John S. Martin adjourned sentencing until April 28, giving Bennett
a chance to win back 10 years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's offer was to reduce Bennett's sentence from 30 years
to 20 years if the Bennetts agreed to surrender a 100-acre horse
farm, a hotel and stock in a racetrack that are in Mrs. Bennett's
name.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Martin said he had concluded that Mrs. Bennett
lied on the witness stand in January when she claimed that she and
her husband did not conspire to put his assets in her name to keep
them away from investors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would take that as a threat,'' said Michael J. Misiaszek.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's office would not say whether Mrs. Bennett is
the subject of a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Bennett used his companies to entice investors
from 46 states into financing bogus leases for office equipment.
Bennett Funding filed for bankruptcy in March 1996, a day after
federal authorities brought fraud charges against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the victims were elderly people who entrusted their life
savings to the company.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has vowed to get back as much money as he can for the
victims. He has given Bennett and his family four chances to return
property to the bankruptcy trustee, who is selling Bennett
companies' assets and repaying creditors owed more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement filed with the court before Martin's remarks,
Mrs. Bennett called the judge's offer ''highly improper'' and
labeled it ''coercion.''
</P>
<P>
   Misiaszek said that he warned Mrs. Bennett to factor in the
possibility of criminal charges against her in weighing her
decision. Mrs. Bennett has not yet made a decision about the
assets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bennett said in documents that she twice tried to turn over
some of her assets to the bankruptcy trustee.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy trustee rejected those offers because they didn't
include all the assets sought by the judge, said the trustee's
lawyer, William Russell. The deal also came with ''significant
strings attached,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Bennett wanted a complete release from every claim we
have against her. We don't want to do that,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bennett has 30 lawsuits brought against her by the
bankruptcy trustee and others, Misiaszek said.
</P>
<P>
   Other court papers filed by Mrs. Bennett include a deed that
identifies her as the sole owner of the horse farm in Oneida, for
sale at $888,000. She also identified herself as the sole owner of
the Comfort Suites Hotel at Vernon Downs racetrack. The hotel is
valued at $3 million but has a debt of $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bennett is afraid that if she turns over the hotel, she
won't have money to support her two young sons, Misiaszek said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's just trying to preserve something for her future and the
future of her children,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
