<HEADLINE> Pataki: Lazio should stay out of Senate race, back Giuliani  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio should stop talking
about being a Rudolph Giuliani alternative for the GOP's Senate
nomination to face Hillary Rodham Clinton, New York state's most
powerful Republican said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it is particularly helpful for other Republicans
to do anything other than get behind the candidacy of Mayor
Giuliani,'' Gov. George Pataki told a state Capitol news
conference. ''I urge him (Lazio) and all the others to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Lazio said he feared the GOP was in danger of losing
the Senate race with Giuliani and offered himself as an
alternative, if party leaders wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Lazio said it appeared unlikely the New York
City mayor could win the backing of the state's Conservative Party.
No Republican in New York has won statewide office without the
support of the Conservative Party since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Republicans need a candidate who can unite the party,
attract Democrats and independents and ''present a better, more
positive, more inclusive message for Republicans.'' The congressman
from Long Island said he didn't think Giuliani was the best
candidate to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's just wrong,'' Pataki said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made it plain months ago that I think the mayor has earned
the right to be our candidate,'' the governor added. ''He has gone
out since that time and mounted an effective campaign. I have every
confidence that he will be our next senator come November.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, state GOP Chairman William Powers had delivered much
the same message. The GOP leader said he had detected no support
among local party leaders across the state for a Lazio candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Wednesday that he didn't want to comment on the
governor's statement until he had a chance to talk personally with
him. The congressman said he had placed a telephone call to Pataki,
but wasn't certain when they would discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''My preference is to deal with this face-to-face,'' the
congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Lazio had said that if Pataki, Powers and other GOP
leaders didn't want him in the Senate race, he wouldn't enter it.
</P>
<P>
   Recent independent polls have shown Giuliani's previous small
lead over Clinton has evaporated in the wake of widespread
criticism of his handling of the fatal shooting last month by New
York City police of an unarmed black man, Patrick Dorismond. In
defending the police, Giuliani released Dorismond's criminal
record, including court-sealed juvenile records.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had been preparing to run for Senate until Pataki threw
his support behind Giuliani in August 1999 and asked Lazio to
suspend his effort. The congressman did so.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said Wednesday that he hoped Giuliani and the leaders of
the Conservative Party, who are close to the governor, could work
out their differences. Michael Long, the chairman of the
Conservative Party, has said Giuliani's continued support for
abortion rights is a stumbling block. The mayor has refused to
budge on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
