<HEADLINE> Brazil Land Reformer Acquitted  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL ASTOR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VITORIA, Brazil (AP) -- Activists applauded the acquittal of a
prominent land reform leader at his retrial on murder charges,
calling it a victory for the international human rights community.
</P>
<P>
   A seven member jury acquitted Jose Rainha Jr. on Wednesday in
the killings of farm owner Jose Macado Neto and an off-duty
policeman during a failed 1989 attempt by rural workers to occupy a
ranch in southeastern Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Rainha's trial, which began Monday in this eastern port city,
has refocused attention on the country's often bloody land
disputes, which have cost more than 1,000 lives over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Rainha was not accused of carrying out the killings, but the
prosecution said he was the ''intellectual author'' of the deaths.
The nine men accused of shooting at the victims remain at large.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was clearly a political trial,'' said Maria Luisa
Mendonca of the human rights group Global Justice. ''The defense
was very strong, and the evidence against him very weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, who described Rainha as a rabble-rouser who incited
the rural workers to violence, relied largely on sworn statements
from neighbors and testimony from people who said they had heard
Rainha was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses for the defense confirmed Rainha's alibi that, on the
day of the shootings, the squatters' leader was in the northeastern
state of Ceara, 1,400 miles away from where the killings took
place.
</P>
<P>
   Mendonca described the verdict as a victory for the
international human rights community. Without attention from
abroad, she said she believes Rainha would have been convicted as
he was once before in 1997, when he was sentenced to 26{ years in
prison. Brazilian law guarantees a retrial for anyone sentenced to
20 years or more for a single crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last trial was clearly unfair,'' said Julia Rochester of
Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Rainha's group organizes invasions of idle land to pressure the
government to speed up agrarian reform in a country where the
richest 20 percent of the people hold 90 percent of the land, while
the poorest 40 percent own just 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and human rights groups said the charges were trumped
up to weaken the movement just as it was gaining support from
middle class Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has definitely been an effort to criminalize the actions
of'' Rainha's group, Mendonca said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters erupted in cheers as the verdict was read and carried
Rainha on their shoulders to a nearby square, where thousands of
movement members had camped out to watch the proceedings on a giant
screen television.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is like divine justice,'' Rainha said following the
verdict. ''It may take a while to arrive, but it always emerges.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they would file an appeal on the grounds that
defense witnesses had communicated with each other during the
trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
