<HEADLINE> Poll: Most Americans Live With Pain  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID PITT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Aches. Soreness. Irritation -- Americans know the
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   A newly released survey shows that 89 percent of U.S. adults
experience pain at least once a month and more than half believe
it's just something people have to live with.
</P>
<P>
   The results have alarmed pain management specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just getting older in the U.S. does not mean you've got to be
in misery and got to be sick all the time,'' Dr. B. Eliot Cole of
Las Vegas, a consultant on pain management, said Wednesday. ''Don't
sell yourself short just because you have a few miles on your
chassis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup survey of 2,002 adults over the age of 18, conducted
for the Arthritis Foundation, found that 46 percent of women and 37
percent of men experience pain daily.
</P>
<P>
   The most common type of pain, reported by 23 percent of the
respondents, was joint pain. Backaches, sore feet and muscle pain
are the next most common ailments. Arthritis was fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Only half the adults visited a doctor for pain in the past three
years. Eighty percent believe aches and pains are just a part of
getting older, and 28 percent believe there is no solution, the
survey found.
</P>
<P>
   The Arthritis Foundation, which is based in Atlanta, released
the survey results Wednesday as part of the launch of a public
information program, ''Speaking of Pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Klippel, the foundation's medical director, said the
survey indicates Americans need to be taught that living with pain
is not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''By talking to a health care provider about their pain, people
can start taking control of their lives by controlling their
pain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A large majority of the survey respondents ages 65 and older --
88 percent -- said they believe getting older is the cause of their
pain, and 69 percent cited arthritis as the reason.
</P>
<P>
   Younger respondents, ages 18-34, attributed their pain to
tension or stress, being overworked or their lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four percent of pain sufferers will see a doctor only when
they cannot stand the pain any longer and 60 percent of the
respondents said pain is something people must live with.
</P>
<P>
   Sophye Hochberg, 25, of Bethesda, Md., said that's not true. She
suffers from chronic pain brought on by a congenital condition and
injuries from a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''People don't realize how many options there are and how many
new things come up. If they find the right pain doctor, you don't
even have to take long-term pain medications,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many survey respondents -- 43 percent -- said pain keeps them from
activities as simple as standing or waiting in line for long
periods of time. Twenty-seven percent said they missed worked in
the past year due to pain.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup results were based on a telephone survey of 1,002
women and 1,000 men ages 18 and older from May 21 to June 9, 1999.
The margin of error was plus or minus 2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Arthritis Foundation: http://www.arthritis.org
</P>
<P>
   American Academy of Pain Management: http://www.aapainmanage.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
