<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turk President's Re-Election Nixed  </HEADLINE>
By SUZAN FRASER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Parliament has put an end to President
Suleyman Demirel's aspirations for re-election, but Turkey's most
enduring leader is far from through with his political career.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the 76-year-old Demirel, who has served as premier
seven times and has been president since 1993, has hinted that he
could return to active politics when his term ends on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''How will I use my energy?'' Demirel said recently. ''Not by
watering flowers or by taking care of chickens. ... I'll find
something to do, no one should worry.''
</P>
<P>
   The government failed to gather enough votes in Parliament on
Wednesday for a constitutional amendment that would have allowed
Demirel, who has dominated Turkish politics for close to 40 years,
to seek a second term as president.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit had been pushing for another term
for Demirel, whom he sees as a stabilizing force.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition parties and several lawmakers from Ecevit's
coalition government refused to back the bill, some arguing that it
was time for Turkey to choose a younger head of state. Presidents
in Turkey are figureheads with limited powers to appoint
governments or reject legislation, but can play the crucial role of
a power broker at a time of political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The government now faces the painful task of finding Demirel's
successor. None of the parties in the coalition government alone
has the majority to elect its own candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a new candidate comes as the government, backed
by a $4 billion IMF loan, has embarked on an ambitious economic
program to fight chronic inflation. The coalition also must reform
Turkey's laws to prepare for full membership in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulty ahead, Ecevit assured the public
Wednesday that there would be no government crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Demirel is out of the running for president, analysts
predict that he will either form a new party or try to snatch back
the leadership of the center-right True Path Party, which he
founded. The party is currently led by former premier Tansu Ciller.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tomorrow, he'll start from zero as though nothing has
happened,'' said Husamettin Cindoruk, once a close aide to Demirel.
''And he'll find a lot of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Long referred to as ''Coban Sulu'' or ''Shepherd Sulu,'' --
diminutive for Suleyman -- because of his peasant origins, Demirel
later earned the affectionate name ''Baba'' or father. But more
recently he has been called ''Sultan Suleyman'' -- an allusion to
the Ottoman sultans' long reigns.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Radikal recently devoted its front page to
pictures of Demirel meeting with a series of world leaders who are
long-dead or who have long since retired.
</P>
<P>
   Demirel, a burly, balding figure, entered politics in 1961. He
captured the leadership of his Justice Party in 1965 and first
became premier at age 40 that year. Since then, he has been a
dominant force in Turkish politics and made spectacular comebacks
despite twice being removed from office by the military.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Turkey's military commanders demanded Demirel's
resignation through an ultimatum broadcast on state radio. Demirel
complied within 24 hours. He was forced out of office again in a
1980 military coup that followed bloody fighting in streets and
university campuses that killed thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   Demirel has endured despite allegations of his brothers' and
nephew's shady business dealings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
