<HEADLINE> Danish Queen To Celebrate Birthday  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTIAN WIENBERG, Associated Press Writers
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Like many modern women, Denmark's
popular Queen Margrethe divides her busy life between her job, her
family and her artistic works.
</P>
<P>
   And the monarch, who turns 60 on April 16, has no plans to slow
down.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has always been my feeling and the way I was brought up
too, that you're in this for life,'' Margrethe said. ''We don't
have the tradition in this country of giving up, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Margrethe is easily the most popular public figure among Danes,
who hold the monarchy sacred despite their egalitarianism.
</P>
<P>
   At noon on her birthday, thousands are expected at the
Amalienborg Castle square, where the Royal Guards will present arms
in their red gala uniforms. Margrethe will appear on the balcony
while the flag-waving crowd will, according to tradition, shout
''hurrah'' seven times.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon she will ride in a carriage through Copenhagen,
escorted by mounted Hussars, and be celebrated at banquets.
</P>
<P>
   Only her oldest son, 31-year-old Crown Prince Frederik will be
absent -- he is participating in a 2,170-mile dogsled trek with five
other members of an elite navy unit.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Frederik would not be able to attend, Margrethe visited
him this week. She flew to Greenland's northernmost point, 310
miles south of the North Pole, bringing along an almond cake.
</P>
<P>
   Margrethe said she is proud of her son but needs a bit of help
communicating with Frederik by e-mail because she hasn't yet
mastered computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are things that I'm not very good at keeping pace with.
I'm very aware of that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark's first reigning queen in five centuries, Margrethe rose
to the throne when her father, King Frederik IX, died in 1972.
Three years earlier she had wed French diplomat Henri Count de
Laborde de Monpezat, who became Prince Henrik. They have two sons,
Prince Frederik and Prince Joachim, 30.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she became grandmother when Joachim's wife, Princess
Alexandra, gave birth to a son.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's wonderful to see the family becoming more numerous,'' the
queen said. ''It makes you think how time passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Margrethe has won praise for her artistic works, which range
from abstract paintings and embroidery of church vestments to
making altar pieces and dinnerware.
</P>
<P>
   She also has illustrated a limited edition of J.R.R. Tolkien's
''The Lord of the Rings'' and designed costumes for television and
theater plays. She most recently co-directed a 28-minute television
movie of Hans Christian Andersen fairy tales.
</P>
<P>
   Margrethe said she enjoys spending evenings with her husband,
listening to music, reading books and playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we ever lack something to do together,'' she
laughed to her husband, who had only one request for his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ''That she goes on being how she is, how she has been. I have no
complaints yet,'' Henrik said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
