<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rowland supports tax credits for private school families  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Minutes after Gov. John G. Rowland
reiterated his strong support for a proposal would give a tax
credit of up to $500 to families who have a child to private
school, opponents were criticizing the plan outside his office.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Citizens Alliance for Public Education ,a group of
parents, teachers, school administrators and civic and religious
leaders, said Wednesday they believe tax money should only be used
in the state's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''This initiative is part of an attack on the institute of
public education,'' said Robert Leikind of the Anti-Defamation
League. ''We think that our public schools need to be invested in,
and strengthened so that all students ... get the benefits of our
tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said the state ranks second in the country in education
spending, employs the highest-paid teachers and has allotted $425
million for the construction of new public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tax credit based on any activity ... has no relation,
connection to any type of other funding,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by three children clad in school uniforms, Rowland
emphasized that ''this is not a voucher program.''
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do with public education,'' he said. ''It does
not take a single penny away from public education.''
</P>
<P>
   What it does, he said, is offer some relief to many working
families throughout the state that spend as much as $20,000 a year
per child on private education. Single state income tax filers
making $50,000 or less and joint filers making $100,000 or less
would be eligible for the credit. Those with incomes too low to pay
state income tax would not be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said this measure ranks in his top three priorities,
along with cutting the gas tax and working on the development of
downtown Hartford. He is asking for a total of $16.5 million to be
spent on the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, there is significant bipartisan support for this
plan,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Tax breaks, Rowland said, are passed every year in Connecticut --
ranging from personal property credits to corporate relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-06-00 0134 </TRAILER>
