<HEADLINE> GOP Defeats Campaign Finance Measure  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are opposing an attempt by
Democrats to force a growing type of tax-exempt political
organization to disclose contributors and expenditures, even though
the groups are targeting politicians in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   GOP members of the House Ways and Means Committee voted against
the measure Wednesday, arguing that it should await broader
campaign finance reform and could drag down an underlying bill that
would expand taxpayer rights and give people breaks on IRS
penalties and interest.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's not weigh down this taxpayer rights bill with
politically charged issues that could be a poison pill,'' said Rep.
Rob Portman, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted 21-15 along party lines to defeat an
amendment by Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, that would require
financial disclosure for tax-exempt groups organized under Section
527 of the tax code. The groups would have to submit financial
information to the Federal Election Commission and detail their
existence to the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett, who may get another chance to offer his amendment next
week on the House floor, said these groups are becoming the
''political super-weapon'' of the 2000 election, one that can
''fill the airwaves with hate and the mailboxes with
disinformation'' without disclosure -- so long as they don't
expressly advocate voting for or against a particular candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 is more than 25 years old, but the law has recently
been embraced by political organizations of every stripe following
court decisions and an IRS opinion that paved the way. They are now
involved in political causes and campaigns across the political
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a group with Republican ties called Shape the
Debate is running TV ads critical of Vice President Al Gore in
California, New York and Washington. Another one called Citizens
for Better Medicare, created by drug manufacturers and their
allies, plans to spend millions of dollars to work against any
legislation that would control prescription prices.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic 2000 presidential nominee, has
called Section 527 groups ''the equivalent of Swiss bank accounts
for campaigns,'' and Congress' Joint Committee on Taxation has also
recommended a series of reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett said putting the issue off was an effort to ''delay,
defer, duck, dodge -- use all kinds of excuses'' to avoid wading
into the controversies of campaign finance reform. He repeatedly
invoked the presidential campaign of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
whose reform message of minimizing big money in politics helped
attract new voters to the GOP -- and who was criticized in ads run
earlier this year by Section 527 groups.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the underlying bill would provide taxpayers
with new protections against improper disclosure of tax
information, allow interest on past-due taxes to be waived if the
IRS made a mistake and prohibit any taxes on interest payments made
by the IRS to the taxpayer. Its total price tag is estimated at
$2.1 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://www.thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
