<HEADLINE> Sharpton plans daily protests for Easter week  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In a move that recalls the month of daily
protests led by the Rev. Al Sharpton in front of Police
Headquarters last year, he has announced plans for a busy week of
civil disobedience leading up to Easter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going back to the streets,'' Sharpton said Wednesday at
a news conference where he was joined by Martin Luther King III and
the families of police shooting victims Amadou Diallo and Patrick
Dorismond. ''This is necessary to put the pressure on the federal
government so that they know that our lives are on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said demonstrations would begin at Federal Plaza in
downtown Manhattan on Monday, April 17, and continue all week with
actions on Wall Street and in the Theater District, among other
locations. Protesters will urge the U.S. Department of Justice to
monitor the New York Police Department and press criminal civil
rights charges against the four officers who killed Diallo in a
barrage of 41 bullets. An Albany jury acquitted them of murder
charges in a state trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call on (Attorney General) Janet Reno to hear the voice of a
mother, woman to woman,'' said Diallo's mother, Kadiatou Diallo.
''Please, you have to hear our calls,'' she said. ''Every night I'm
waking up, every night I'm crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sharpton organized a month of daily protests outside
Police Headquarters after Diallo's death. More than 1,200 people
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton also urged New Yorkers to forego buying special Easter
clothes and supplies this year to send a message that life should
not continue as usual in the face of racial profiling and police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to wear overalls on Easter Sunday,'' he said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond's parents, his two daughters, and his brother and
sister sat beside Sharpton as he spoke, as did King, the son of the
slain civil rights leader. Dorismond, an unarmed, off-duty security
guard, was killed by undercover police in a botched drug sting last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton and King said they planned to lead a rally against
racial profiling and police misconduct near the Lincoln Memorial in
Washington on Aug. 28, the 37th anniversary of Martin Luther King
Jr.'s ''I Have a Dream'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that my father would be here if he were alive, joining
these families, calling for the Justice Department to come in,''
the younger King said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, about 700 people rallied near City Hall, and
one group was removed by police after briefly blocking traffic on
the Brooklyn Bridge. Eighteen people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The angry protesters, many of them high school and college
students, chanted ''Giuliani must go!'' referring to New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, and waved signs that said ''Stop the murder of
our youth!'' Also present were people who said they had lost
relatives in confrontations with police.
</P>
<P>
   The rally began at Union Square, and demonstrators walked down
Broadway to City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just enraged about what's been going on in this city,''
said Meryl Feigenberg, 17, of the Bronx, a student at La Guardia
High School.
</P>
<P>
   ''Four cops killed a man and nothing happened to them,'' she
said. ''We're showing them we're taking a stand for this and won't
let it happen anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
