<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Tax Rollback Faces Uphill Climb  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott's
election-year proposal to roll back federal gasoline taxes because
of soaring pump prices is facing an increasingly uphill climb.
</P>
<P>
   As it continued debate today on a $1.83 trillion budget for next
year, the Senate was likely to easily approve a bipartisan
amendment opposing Lott's plan. The Mississippi Republican has
proposed erasing the 4.3 cent-a-gallon gasoline tax increase
enacted in 1993, and suspending the entire 18.4 cent-a-gallon tax
if the average pump price of a gallon of regular unleaded tops $2
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Faith in snake oil never seems to diminish in the halls of
Congress,'' Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said Wednesday, arguing that
reducing the gasoline tax would have little impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''We might as well hire a witch doctor to shake a tambourine
over the heads'' of the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting
Countries as reduce the gasoline tax, he said. Cutbacks in OPEC oil
production led to big spike in gasoline and home heating oil prices
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Byrd's provision was non-binding and Lott and his
supporters were unlikely to give up completely, the vote was
expected to spotlight how difficult it will be for him to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   House GOP leaders already have all but abandoned the idea amid
lawmakers' concerns that it could dry up federal road-building
funds. Instead, they have focused on tax breaks for producers and
proposals to open up more federal lands to oil drilling.
</P>
<P>
   In a related amendment, Sen. William Roth, R-Del., was trying to
kill a budget provision that assumes the government will earn $1.2
billion by allowing oil to be taken from the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge in Alaska. That fight pits the Clinton
administration and environmentalists against the oil industry and
its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of barrels of oil could lie under the Arctic refuge,
but no drilling is allowed there. Supporters of drilling in the
refuge say it is a potential answer to the United States'
dependence on foreign sources of oil.
</P>
<P>
   ''This senator is not going to stand by and support increased
dependence on Iraq,'' said Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The battleground for the oil fights was the 2001 budget, which
sets tax and spending totals but leaves details for later
legislation. The House approved a similar spending plan on March
24. President Clinton's signature is not required.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to rising gasoline prices has blossomed into a
political battle, with Republicans accusing Clinton and Vice
President Gore of having an ineffective energy policy. Gore, the
presumptive Democratic presidential candidate, cast the Senate's
tie-breaking vote when Congress boosted the gasoline tax seven
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has blamed Congress for letting his authority lapse last
week to tap government oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd and his supporters say the gasoline tax rollback would have
little effect on consumers or OPEC. It also could cost billions of
dollars in federal revenue used for road projects, they say.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC is the 11-member organization that cut oil production last
year in an effort to boost prices. Since then, gasoline pump prices
have ballooned as crude oil prices tripled beyond $30 a barrel,
though they have since fallen to the mid-$20s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-06-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000406.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NH Justice Tells of Violations  </HEADLINE>
By HOLLY RAMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. -- A constitutional crisis over alleged ethics
violations at the New Hampshire Supreme Court may worsen following
damaging disclosures by the state's top prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Philip McLaughlin touched off the
unprecedented crisis last Friday with a report concluding it was an
''institutional practice'' for the court's justices to participate
in cases in which they had a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   For five days, past and present justices said they read and
commented on such cases only to make grammar, punctuation or
similarly benign corrections. But Justice Sherman Horton told
investigators otherwise last month, according to an interview in
119 pages of investigative documents released by McLaughlin on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Horton said justices who disqualified themselves from cases
still offered opinions ''about why, as a matter of law, he
disagrees with the result,'' an investigator wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Justice Horton went on to say it's probably not right, but
it's done with a purpose to improve the outcome of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Horton, who did not return a phone message left at his home
Wednesday night, did not cite any cases. But his comments were at
odds with ones he made to investigators a week earlier when he said
comments by recused justices were ''not intended to change the
outcome'' of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the disclosure, however, some legislators called on
Chief Justice David Brock to resign or face impeachment, and said
two other justices on the five-member court also were tainted.
Legislative leaders said they wanted to get all the facts before
acting.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin's report Friday accused Justice Stephen Thayer of
criminal ethics violations, including trying to exert improper
influence in his wife's appeal of their divorce case. Thayer's
lawyer said he would have been acquitted, but Thayer resigned
rather than face prosecution and further damage the court's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new documents, Thayer insisted several times to
other justices he was not alone in making substantive comments on
cases after disqualifying himself.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer refused to be interviewed by prosecutors and, through his
lawyer, declined to comment Wednesday. But according to one
document, Horton recalled Thayer saying, ''There are many instances
where you guys comment on cases you are recused from, too,'' the
documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said Thayer made a similar comment to him Feb. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-06-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000406.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Fighting for Hispanic Voters  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE KOIDIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- He's the Hispanic mayor of a Texas
Democratic stronghold, but Carlos Ramirez not only supports
Republican George W. Bush for president, he even traveled to New
Hampshire and California to campaign for him.
</P>
<P>
   He's just the kind of person Bush wants on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore, too.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidential candidates are vigorously courting local
leaders like Ramirez this year, as well as Hispanics in general.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's fastest-growing group of voters, Hispanics are
projected to account for 5.4 percent of the electorate this fall.
Even more important, four states with large Hispanic populations --
Texas, California, New York and Florida -- hold 144 of the 270
electoral votes needed to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The country's Hispanic vote has gone overwhelmingly to the
Democrats in the past two presidential elections. But Bush is
running about even with Gore in national polling, and the Texas
governor has said repeatedly he won't concede the Hispanic vote
this year.
</P>
<P>
   And neither will the GOP. The Republican National Committee
plans to spend $7 million to $10 million this year on a media
campaign reaching out to Hispanics, including an ad unveiled
Wednesday that is being tested in Fresno, Calif., which has a
sizable Latino population.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore, the Democratic vice president, use
Spanish-language ads in targeted areas and switch quickly to
Spanish when speaking to Hispanic crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has touted his 1998 Texas re-election as evidence of his
appeal. He captured as much as 49 percent of the Hispanic vote in
Texas that year, according to some exit polling, though other
polling put the figure lower.
</P>
<P>
   This year, one contest that might be instructive for the fall
was California's primary, which included voters of all parties.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won a majority of Hispanics. Bush got about one in five
Hispanic votes, poorer than his showing among non-Hispanics. John
McCain won nearly as many Hispanics as Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls found Bush winning Hispanics in equally overwhelming
majorities as non-Hispanics in Florida and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Hispanic vote, largely concentrated in New York
City, tends to be Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Bush could be helped by the Elian Gonzalez controversy in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans there, unlike a majority of Hispanics elsewhere
in the country, tend to vote Republican. President Clinton and Gore
won the state in their 1996 re-election, but Gore's recent comments
on the Gonzalez case have not been well-received in the Miami area.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Texas, in an exit poll conducted in El Paso on
March 14, the day of the Texas presidential primary, 26 percent of
Hispanics said they voted for Bush, while 67.5 percent said they
voted for Gore, said Gregory Rocha, associate professor of
political science at the University of Texas at El Paso. The poll
had a margin of error of plus or minus 5.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that Mr. Bush can just assume that because he
did fairly well in the general election in '98 that this group is
sold on him,'' Rocha said.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   The two-term mayor of this border city, who identifies himself
as a ''conservative Democrat,'' says the Bush camp solicited his
help for the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramirez says, ''My support for him is because I have gotten
to know him as a person. I have gotten to know his values. I know I
can trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez is ''the kind of figure Mr. Bush can point to bolster
his claim of representing the broad center as a 'compassionate
conservative,''' said Bruce Buchanan, political scientist at the
University of Texas-Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has split from fellow Republicans in ways that could help
him with some Hispanics. While former California Gov. Pete Wilson
backed measures such as Proposition 187, which sought to end
government benefits for illegal immigrants, Bush advocated public
education for undocumented immigrant children. He supports
beefed-up border enforcement but believes in helping people already
here.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has made several trips to Mexico and supports the
North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
