<HEADLINE> Lee stepping down as public safety commissioner and head of crimelab  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- State Public Safety Commissioner Henry
Lee says he plans to retire July 1 in order to spend more time
investigating unsolved murders as a forensic scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also plans to step down as head of the state crime lab, a
position he has held for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to slow down the pace and work on cold cases, teaching
and training,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is a world-renowned forensics' expert who has testified in
the trials of O.J. Simpson and William Kennedy Smith. He is
currently working on other high-profile cases including the
investigation into the slaying of child beauty queen JonBenet
Ramsey in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Lee took over as commissioner in May 1998, replacing Waterbury
State's Attorney John Connelly, who wanted to return to the
courtroom. Lee was the fourth commissioner appointed by Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   Lee originally told the governor he would do the job for a year,
but relented and stayed another year. He said it was important to
finish some outstanding projects such as completing the installment
of the new radio system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have finished the projects I promised the governor I would
get done and now it is time to step back,'' Lee said. He said he
plans to meet with the governor to discuss his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Former Hartford Superior Court Judge Arthur Spada is among those
being considered for the post, said Dean Pagani, Rowland's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Spada is best known for conducting the grand jury into Hartford
police corruption in the mid-1990s. A total of eight officers were
indicted; two have been acquitted at trials.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm honored that the governor includes me as one of the people
on his list of candidates,'' Spada said.
</P>
<P>
   Pagani would not discuss other candidates or whether Rowland is
intent on naming someone from outside the state police agency as
the new commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think you can see a trend with the last two commissioners of
the governor looking outside the agency,'' Pagani said.
</P>
</TEXT>
