<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Deplores Fight Over Elian  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke
with sadness about the plight of Elian Gonzalez, and there was
obvious disappointment when she talked about the might-have-beens
in U.S.-Cuban relations.
</P>
<P>
   Albright knows something about both topics, being the
grandmother of a boy who, like Elian, is 6, and having spent a good
part of her life studying ways of changing communist regimes.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday with Associated Press editors and
reporters, Albright said she was perplexed that the Elian case
remained unresolved after more than four months. ''It's a terrible,
terrible issue,'' she said. ''It's the question of a child needing
to be with its natural parent and the desire for that child to have
a good life. It's very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the interview came word that Elian's father, who
had received his U.S. visa on Tuesday, was coming to the United
States today, raising the possibility he would take temporary
custody of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been living with his great-uncle in Miami since being
rescued off the coast of Florida in November.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also disclosed in the interview that the administration
years ago had thought about developing a new approach to Cuba with
a view toward promoting change.
</P>
<P>
   As a native of Eastern Europe who watched communist regimes
there become demoralized and eventually collapse, Albright
suggested the prospect of change in Cuba intrigued her and others
in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Castro himself has, not surprisingly, brushed aside the notion
that Cuba needs a transition. ''We had our transition in 1959,'' he
has said, referring to the year he took power.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright, recalling President Clinton's early years in
office, said, ''There was a desire among all of us to see whether
something could be different about the relationship with Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   What put change out of reach, she said, was the Cuban decision
to use MiG fighters to shoot down two unarmed, Miami-based private
planes over international waters north of Cuba in 1996. Three U.S.
citizens of Cuban origin were killed. A fourth who died was a
Cuban-American permanent resident of South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That incident, Albright said, ''made it very difficult to pursue
change.''
</P>
<P>
   The degree to which U.S.-Cuban relations has sunk is symbolized
by an ''anti-imperialist'' monument which was inaugurated this week
in Havana near the U.S. diplomatic mission.
</P>
<P>
   ''It strikes me that the cost of that monument, the money, might
have been better spent on helping the poor people of Cuba,''
Albright said. ''The question I always have about any of these
dictators is are they really interested in their people.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright believes the 1996 attack was a calculated attempt by
Castro to undercut U.S. policy, enshrined at the time in the Cuba
Democracy Act of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The law tightened the embargo on the one hand while opening the
way for donations of food and medicine to Cuba as well as
people-to-people exchanges. Albright said Castro was angry because
the U.S. policy was working. He complained particularly about the
exchanges, calling them subversive.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging over more than a dozen foreign policy issues -- and
saying it is far too soon for her to consider what she might do
when her term as secretary of state ends in January -- Albright also
said:
</P>
<P>
   --American officials are sounding out Russian President Vladimir
Putin about holding a summit meeting with Clinton. Saying they have
much to talk about, Albright called Putin ''a pragmatic man who has
to get through a large agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   --She will keep insisting that any U.S. dialogue with Iran
include U.S. allegations that Iran sponsors terrorism and seeks to
acquire weapons of mass destruction. Earlier Wednesday, Iran's
foreign minister, Kamal Kharrazi, said in Tehran that her
groundbreaking proposal last month to reverse more than two decades
of distrust was welcome and had some positive points.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said the overture was marred by continuing U.S.
hostility. He called for ''practical steps'' to show the policy has
been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   --The United States, in easing sanctions against Iraq so it could
sell more oil and import more food, was mindful of Arab concerns
that the Iraqi people were being victimized by the U.S.-organized
boycott.
</P>
<P>
   -- The United States was preparing to help Israel find an
''internationally legitimized way'' of withdrawing its troops from
southern Lebanon in July. The administration prefers a pullout be
part of an overall accord between Israel and Syria, but
negotiations were shelved indefinitely in mid-January, and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak seems to determined to withdraw
unilaterally this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
