<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latest Space Crew Docks With Mir  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Two Russian cosmonauts linked up with the Mir
space station today in a mission to bring the aging craft back to
life after it circled Earth unoccupied for eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Zalyotin and Alexander Kaleri, who lifted off from the
Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakstan on Tuesday, docked flawlessly with
the space station on autopilot, officials at Mission Control said.
</P>
<P>
   The ground crew, packed in the mission control room, burst into
applause as the cosmonauts' space capsule connected with Mir,
relieved that there were no problems docking with the unmanned
station.
</P>
<P>
   The last crew to man the space station returned to Earth in
August when the cash-strapped Russian space program decided to get
rid of the 14-year-old orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   But space officials put off the station's destruction date
indefinitely after MirCorp, based in Amsterdam, Netherlands, agreed
to pay $10 million to $20 million to lease commercial rights to the
station.
</P>
<P>
   MirCorp has said it is considering various ventures aboard Mir,
including opening it up for well-heeled tourists. Under the
agreement, Mir remains Russian-owned and available for Russian
scientific use.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials continue to insist that Mir is good for
several more years in orbit, even though it has been plagued by
accidents and breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The most terrifying were a fire and a near-fatal crash in 1997
when an unmanned supply ship docking with the station strayed off
course. The ship punctured one of the station's modules, which had
to be sealed off for good.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the station, Zalyotin and Kaleri will concentrate on
plugging a small air leak that developed this summer. Shortly
before the last crew left, officials noticed that the station was
slowly losing oxygen, but said patching it could wait.
</P>
<P>
   The two were also expected to go on a spacewalk to conduct
several scientific experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The mission had been originally set to last for 45 days, but
officials extended it to 60 days after cutting Russian actor
Vladimir Steklov from the crew. His flight was scrapped after
filmmakers failed to pay the multimillion-dollar tab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
