<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eifman Uses Ballet for Human Drama  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''The Red Giselle'' bursts like skyrockets
across the stage, delivering a highly charged drama enacted by the
superb dancers of the Eifman Ballet of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The steps are classical ballet, used in modern combinations.
Unlike George Balanchine's neoclassical plotless ballets, which
emphasized interesting movement, the intent of choreographer Boris
Eifman is drama. It reminds a viewer of choreographer Maurice
Bejart but has more substance and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Red Giselle'' was performed for the first of seven times
on Wednesday at the City Center. After a three-week season ends
here April 16, the company will dance in Boston, Minneapolis,
Chicago, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Dallas, Denver and Colorado
Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The ballet is based on the life of Russian ballerina Olga
Spessivtseva, considered the greatest romantic ballerina of her
generation. Born in 1895, she left Russia at age 28, danced in the
Paris Opera Ballet from 1924 to 1932, suffered depression, moved to
the United States, spent 20 years in a mental hospital and ended
her life living with Russians on a New York farm maintained by
writer Leo Tolstoy's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Red Giselle'' begins in a ballet class, with a stern
teacher, danced by Sergei Basalaev, singling out Spessivtseva,
danced by Yelena Kuzmina. The ballerina attracts a secret police
agent, danced by Albert Galichanin, who meets her backstage.
</P>
<P>
   They have a fascinating pas de deux in which he dominates by
force and near cruelty. He grasps her arm instead of her hand and
turns, pulls and lifts her, sometimes over his head. She looks
helpless, often limply falls forward. But when he lets go of her,
she reaches out to him. He puts his coat around her, baring his
muscled arms, and carries her out.
</P>
<P>
   She dances in front of a ragamuffin mob; the teacher is
symbolically tortured. Kuzmina and Galichanin have another duet,
obviously a love duet, but when he swirls her around it's
deliberately not pretty and full of anguish on both sides. Finally
he lets her go and she runs out and climbs a gangplank, leaving
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In Act 2, in Paris, she falls in love with a dancer (portrayed
by Igor Markov), but he has a male lover. Act 2 has an abbreviated
Act 1 of the famous ballet ''Giselle,'' along with a lively
balletic Charleston scene in a Paris nightclub, featuring women in
chic flapper dresses. The ballerina sees visions there of her
former lover. She has begun to go mad, put in a straitjacket and
imprisoned in a transparent dome.
</P>
<P>
   She is then released to dance some of ''Giselle'' Act 2. The
ending is quietly sad; when the ballerina bows, her surroundings
suggest a room in a mental hospital -- typical of the ingenious
staging that helps make this production a triumph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-06-00 1249 </TRAILER>
