<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Reviews ''House Arrest''  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Critic
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Not many actresses would have the audacity to
portray Thomas Jefferson AND George Stephanopoulos AND Walt Whitman
AND Gloria Steinem -- all in one play.
</P>
<P>
   But in ''House Arrest,'' author and solo performer Anna Deavere
Smith doesn't shirk from trying on more than one hat, even when
several are less than perfect fits.
</P>
<P>
   ''House Arrest,'' Smith's latest epic endeavor, has been
subtitled ''A Search for American Character In and Around the White
House,'' and her one-woman expedition, now on view at
off-Broadway's Public Theater, is exhausting. Exhausting, yet often
fascinating in its attempt to make sense out of what the presidency
does to the people in and around it.
</P>
<P>
   The play, culled from hundreds of interviews, is not as focused
as Smith's previous works, ''Fires in the Mirror'' -- dealing with
the tense relationship between blacks and Jews in Brooklyn's Crown
Heights -- or ''Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992,'' which examined the
rioting after the police beating of Rodney King.
</P>
<P>
   In ''House Arrest,'' Smith wanders through more than 200 years
of American history, although she concentrates on the present,
particularly the Clinton years and Monica Lewinsky. The woman is a
sharp interviewer and a thorough scholar, maybe too enamored of her
own research.
</P>
<P>
   Smith makes some intriguing comparisons between how the press
dealt with the presidency in the past -- not publicly acknowledging
the private foibles of chief executives -- and how today it delves
into every personal detail: Not only the present president, but
those of long ago, judging from the play's extended fascination
with Jefferson and his affair with Sally Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Race threads its way through ''House Arrest,'' with the
consequences of slavery echoing into the present day.
Assassinations, from Lincoln to Kennedy, also make their mark. Ann
Richards, former governor of Texas, chillingly describes events in
Dallas on Nov. 22, 1963, and how she learned about the Kennedy
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The author opens and closes the show with a lively impersonation
of Chicago author Studs Terkel. When asked to name the defining
moment in American history, the impish raconteur can't come up with
one.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he laments what he calls ''moral slippage,'' a term he
says came out of the Nixon White House. Terkel sees this decline as
emblematic of what is wrong with the country, and his interviewer
would seem to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's portrayal of Terkel is quirky, not exactly spot-on, but
it is enough of an approximation to work. Other impersonations are
less successful, particularly her Jefferson and a subdued, somber
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The physical production has been directed by Jo Bonney. It is
top-heavy with props, slides, costume changes and busy bits of
scenery, forever trundling on and off stage. But then, Smith's
effort is mammoth, more than a full evening of theater. A little
trimming would go a long way toward making this ''House Arrest'' a
more theatrical, fast-paced confinement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-06-00 1651 </TRAILER>
