<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aspirin Said OK for Stroke Victims  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Aspirin works just as well in preventing a second
stroke as a more risky blood thinner normally given to stroke
victims with irregular heartbeats just after the attack, according
to new research that experts say could help save thousands of lives
a year.
</P>
<P>
   People with irregular heartbeats who have had strokes are
susceptible to a second, major stroke soon afterward. They normally
are given a blood thinner called heparin to prevent clots, which
can cause a stroke by traveling to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether to use blood thinners in stroke victims
with erratic heartbeats and how potent they should be is
contentious, mainly because of the potential for internal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Heparin, which prevents clots through a different mechanism than
aspirin, has been used for years in such cases, but without any
scientific evidence that it is useful, said Dr. Karen Furie, a
neurologist at Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But a Norwegian study published this week in The Lancet medical
journal found heparin is no better than aspirin, which carries less
risk of hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   ''We needed this evidence. This study answered an important
question and will have far-reaching consequences,'' said Furie,
adding that the results could help save thousands of lives
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional therapy involves an intravenous drip of heparin to
regulate the thickness of the blood or intermittent injections of a
different form of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Although aspirin carries less chance of bleeding, it has been
thought not to be potent enough to be used during the initial
two-week phase of stroke recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In the experiment by scientists at Ulleval University Hospital
in Oslo, 449 men and women with irregular heartbeats were given
either aspirin or heparin about 30 hours after having a stroke
caused by a blood clot traveling to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, the drugs were continued for 14 days, the period
when a patient is most vulnerable to complications, such as another
stroke. The patients were about 80 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the incidence of a recurrent stroke
was about the same in the two groups -- 8.5 percent for those taking
heparin and 7.5 percent for those taking aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   There also was no difference between the two treatments when it
came to other complications of stroke, such as brain hemorrhage or
death.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our study clarifies a long-term controversy ... and supports
use of aspirin instead of heparins,'' said the study's lead author,
Dr. Eivind Berge.
</P>
<P>
   Strokes are the third-leading killer in the United States,
striking about 600,000 people a year and killing about 160,000 of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Blood clots traveling to the brain cause about 60 percent of all
strokes, and an irregular heart leads to about a quarter of those
types of strokes, Furie said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will have a large impact,'' Furie said, adding that the
findings also could apply to other types of stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But she warned against people taking aspirin by themselves after
suffering a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   While most strokes are caused by a blood clot, some happen when
a vein ruptures, in which case taking an aspirin to thin the blood
would be a very bad idea. It is impossible to tell without seeing a
doctor what caused a stroke, Furie said.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian study was conducted at a time when new drugs are
being developed to limit brain damage caused by strokes and prevent
additional strokes from occurring.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the FDA approved a drug called Aggrenox that combines
aspirin with another blood thinner to prevent clots. It is for
patients who have suffered a full-blown stroke or a mini-stroke
called a transient ischemic attack and are at high risk of
suffering another stroke within days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
